public class DataTypesExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // integer data type
        int num1 = 10;
        Integer num2 = 20; // wrapping Integer object around int value

        // floating point data type
        float num3 = 10.5f; // f suffix to denote float
        double num4 = 20.7;

        // character data type
        char ch = 'A';

        // boolean data type
        boolean isTrue = true;

        // outputting the variables to the console
        System.out.println("Integer values: " + num1 + ", " + num2);
        System.out.println("Floating point values: " + num3 + ", " + num4);
        System.out.println("Character value: " + ch);
        System.out.println("Boolean value: " + isTrue);
    }
}
```

This program demonstrates the use of integer, floating point, character, and boolean data types. It also demonstrates the use of wrapper classes like `Integer` to wrap primitive data types. The output of this program would be:

```
Integer values: 10, 20
Floating point values: 10.5, 20.7
Character value: A
Boolean value: true
```

