import java.util.Scanner;

public class LoopsExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);

        // for loop
        System.out.print("Enter a number: ");
        int num1 = scanner.nextInt();

        for (int i = 1; i <= num1; i++) {
            System.out.print(i + " ");
        }
        System.out.println(); // new line

        // while loop
        System.out.print("Enter another number: ");
        int num2 = scanner.nextInt();

        int i = 1;
        while (i <= num2) {
            System.out.print(i + " ");
            i++;
        }
        System.out.println(); // new line

        // do-while loop
        System.out.print("Enter a final number: ");
        int num3 = scanner.nextInt();

        int j = 1;
        do {
            System.out.print(j + " ");
            j++;
        } while (j <= num3);
        System.out.println(); // new line

        scanner.close();
    }
}
```

This program demonstrates the use of for loops, while loops, and do-while loops. It prompts the user to enter input, iterates a certain number of times based on that input, and outputs the results to the console. The output of this program would depend on user input, but it may look something like this:

```
Enter a number: 5
1 2 3 4 5 
Enter another number: 3
1 2 3 
Enter a final number: 7
1 2 3 4 5 6 7 
```

